  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What's the best residential ISP in San Francisco?",
  "response": "The \"best\" residential Internet Service Provider (ISP) in San Francisco can vary depending on specific needs such as speed, reliability, customer service, and price. However, based on general user reviews and industry reports, here are some of the top ISPs in San Francisco:\n\n### Top ISPs in San Francisco:\n\n1. **Xfinity (Comcast)**\n   - **Pros**: \n     - Widespread availability\n     - High-speed options (up to 1,200 Mbps in some areas)\n     - Competitive pricing\n   - **Cons**: \n     - Data caps on some plans\n     - Mixed customer service reviews\n\n2. **AT&T**\n   - **Pros**: \n     - Fiber-optic options (AT&T Fiber) available in some areas, offering up to 1,000 Mbps\n     - Reliable service in areas with fiber coverage\n   - **Cons**: \n     - Limited fiber availability; many customers are still on DSL\n     - Pricing can be higher than competitors\n\n3. **Sonic**\n   - **Pros**: \n     - Known for excellent customer service\n     - No data caps\n     - Fiber-optic options available in select areas\n   - **Cons**: \n     - Limited coverage within San Francisco\n     - Can be more expensive\n\n4. **Webpass (now part of Google Fiber)**\n   - **Pros**: \n     - High-speed internet without data caps\n     - Reliable service\n   - **Cons**: \n     - Limited availability within San Francisco\n     - Acquisition by Google Fiber may change service dynamics\n\n### How to Choose:\n\n- **Speed Needs**: If you need high-speed internet for streaming, gaming, or working from home, consider Xfinity or AT&T Fiber if available.\n- **Customer Service**: Sonic is highly praised for customer service.\n- **Pricing**: Compare introductory offers and long-term costs. Be wary of promotional pricing that increases after the initial period.\n- **Reliability and Coverage**: Check coverage maps and talk to neighbors about their experiences.\n\n### Additional Tips:\n\n- **Check Availability**: Use the ISPs' websites to check availability at your specific address.\n- **Read Reviews**: Look at recent customer reviews on sites like Yelp, Google, and the Better Business Bureau.\n- **Bundles**: Consider if you want to bundle internet with TV or phone services, as this can affect your choice.\n\nIn summary, **Xfinity** is a strong contender due to its widespread availability and high-speed options, but for those in areas with access to **AT&T Fiber** or **Sonic**, these might provide better overall experiences due to superior customer service and no data caps. Always check the latest deals and coverage maps before making a decision.",
